As we do not possess anything but fragments of the New Comedy, from which the Roman dramatists borrowed, it is impossible to estimate the amount of originality‚ which belongs to any play of Plautus taken as a whole ; but the ease and vigour of his language would show clearly that he was treating his models with some freedom‚ if this fact were not also evident from the numerous Roman allusions, to which reference has already been made.

Plautus and his audience. Plautus’ early connexion with the stage gave him the experience requisite sor writing a good acting play. We see it in the broad humour of the dialogum, in the variety of the action, and in the dramatic character os the situations. And, besides he knew well for whom he was writing3 and his audience was not of a high class. The greater the extravagance, the more amusement it gave ; and it is to the knowledge ol this that we must attribute the production os part ol the fourth act of the T rinummus. We can imagine how the excitable spectators screamed with laughter when the Syco- phant calmly declared that Arabia was in PontuS, and how eagerly they waited to see if his effrontery would support him in declaring that he had positively been introduced to Jove.
